<leg:level id="UCPN.SC.SCR70.PT78.D10.SD1"><leg:level-vrnt leveltype="subdivision" searchtype="LEGISLATION SUBDIVISION" subdoc="false" toc-caption="Subdivision 1 Caveat against grant of probate or administration [r 66]">
<leg:heading><desig searchtype="SUBDIV-NUM"><designum><refpt id="UCPN.SC.SCR70.PT78.D10.SD1" type="ext"/>Subdivision 1</designum></desig><title searchtype="SUBDIV-TITLE">Caveat against grant of probate or administration [r 66]</title></leg:heading>
<leg:levelbody>
<leg:level id="UCPN.SC.SCR70.PT78.R66"><leg:level-vrnt leveltype="rul" searchtype="LEGISLATION RUL" subdoc="true" toc-caption="[SCR Pt 78 r 66] r 66 Caveat against grant of probate or administration">
<leg:levelinfo>
<leg:levelstatus isrepealed="false" ln.user-displayed="false"/></leg:levelinfo>
<leg:heading inline="true"><edpnum><refpt id="UCPN.SC.SCR70.PT78.R66" type="ext"/>[SCR Pt 78 r 66]</edpnum><title searchtype="RUL-TITLE">Caveat against grant of probate or administration</title><desig searchtype="RUL-NUM"><designum>66</designum></desig></leg:heading>
<leg:levelbody>
<leg:bodytext>
<glp:note>
<p><text><ci:cite searchtype="LEG-REF" type="legref"><ci:content>(cf former Part 78, rule 61)</ci:content></ci:cite></text></p></glp:note>
</leg:bodytext>
<leg:level id="UCPN.SC.SCR70.PT78.R66.1"><leg:level-vrnt leveltype="subrul" searchtype="LEGISLATION SUBRUL">
<leg:levelinfo>
<leg:levelstatus isrepealed="false" ln.user-displayed="false"/></leg:levelinfo>
<leg:heading inline="true"><desig><designum><refpt id="UCPN.SC.SCR70.PT78.R66.1" type="ext"/>(1)</designum></desig></leg:heading>
<leg:levelbody>
<leg:bodytext>
<p><text>A person who claims an interest in an estate may file a caveat in respect of any grant of probate or administration, or resealing of a foreign grant, being made in respect of the estate.</text></p>
</leg:bodytext>
</leg:levelbody>
</leg:level-vrnt>
</leg:level>
<leg:level id="UCPN.SC.SCR70.PT78.R66.2"><leg:level-vrnt leveltype="subrul" searchtype="LEGISLATION SUBRUL">
<leg:levelinfo>
<leg:levelstatus isrepealed="false" ln.user-displayed="false"/></leg:levelinfo>
<leg:heading inline="true"><desig><designum><refpt id="UCPN.SC.SCR70.PT78.R66.2" type="ext"/>(2)</designum></desig></leg:heading>
<leg:levelbody>
<leg:bodytext>
<p><text>The caveat must state fully the nature of the interest claimed by the caveator and an address for service.</text></p>
</leg:bodytext>
</leg:levelbody>
</leg:level-vrnt>
</leg:level>
<leg:level id="UCPN.SC.SCR70.PT78.R66.3"><leg:level-vrnt leveltype="subrul" searchtype="LEGISLATION SUBRUL">
<leg:levelinfo>
<leg:levelstatus isrepealed="false" ln.user-displayed="false"/></leg:levelinfo>
<leg:heading inline="true"><desig><designum><refpt id="UCPN.SC.SCR70.PT78.R66.3" type="ext"/>(3)</designum></desig></leg:heading>
<leg:levelbody>
<leg:bodytext>
<p><text>If the caveator is aware that any other person is making, or is intending to make, an application for the grant of probate or administration, or the resealing of a foreign grant, in respect of the same estate, the caveator must, within 7 days after filing the caveat, serve a copy of the caveat on that other person.</text></p>
</leg:bodytext>
</leg:levelbody>
</leg:level-vrnt>
</leg:level>
<leg:bodytext>
<leg:comntry subdoc="true" toc-caption="NOTES"><heading searchtype="COMMENTARY"><title><refpt id="UCPN.SC.SCR70.PT78.R66.COM1" type="ext"/>NOTES</title></heading>
<level id="UCPN_SC.SGM_UCPN.SC.SCR70.PT78.R66-1" leveltype="para0" subdoc="true" toc-caption="[SCR Pt 78.66.1] Approved form"><heading searchtype="COMMENTARY"><edpnum><refpt id="UCPN.SC.SCR70.PT78.R66-1" type="ext"/>[SCR Pt 78.66.1] </edpnum><title>Approved form</title></heading>
<bodytext searchtype="COMMENTARY">
<p>
<text>The approved form for a caveat against an application for the grant or resealing of probate or administration is UCPR Form 141.</text></p>
</bodytext>
</level><level id="UCPN_SC.SGM_UCPN.SC.SCR70.PT78.R66-5" leveltype="para0" subdoc="true" toc-caption="[SCR Pt 78.66.5] Nature and purpose of caveat"><heading searchtype="COMMENTARY"><edpnum><refpt id="UCPN.SC.SCR70.PT78.R66-5" type="ext"/>[SCR Pt 78.66.5] </edpnum><title>Nature and purpose of caveat</title></heading>
<bodytext searchtype="COMMENTARY">
<p>
<text>Section 144 of the Probate and Administration Act 1898 allows a person to lodge in the court registry a caveat against any application for a grant or resealing of probate or administration. The lodging of a caveat does not of itself commence proceedings: <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseref ID="cr003019" spanref="cr003019-001" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="P"/><ci:edition><ci:date year="1923"/></ci:edition><ci:page num="184"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Re Emery</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr003019-001" status="unval">[1923] P 184</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="95707" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>. Its effect is to require notice to be given to the caveator before the Court can proceed to deal with the substantive application: <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseref ID="cr003020" spanref="cr003020-001" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="VLR"/><ci:edition><ci:date year="1942"/></ci:edition><ci:page num="125"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref ID="cr003021" spanref="cr003021-002" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="ALR"/><ci:edition><ci:date year="1942"/></ci:edition><ci:page num="167"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Re Emery; Re Finn</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr003020-001" status="unval">[1942] VLR 125</ci:span>; <ci:span spanid="cr003021-002" status="unval">[1942] ALR 167</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="95705" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite> and Probate and Administration Act 1898 ss 145 and 146.</text></p>
</bodytext>
</level><level id="UCPN_SC.SGM_UCPN.SC.SCR70.PT78.R66-10" leveltype="para0" subdoc="true" toc-caption="[SCR Pt 78.66.10] Types of caveat"><heading searchtype="COMMENTARY"><edpnum><refpt id="UCPN.SC.SCR70.PT78.R66-10" type="ext"/>[SCR Pt 78.66.10] </edpnum><title>Types of caveat</title></heading>
<bodytext searchtype="COMMENTARY">
<p>
<text>Caveats are lodged by persons who claim an interest in the deceased&#x2019;s estate and are usually a preliminary step to contentious proceedings between the applicant for probate and the caveator. A caveat generally lapses after 6 months, but it may be withdrawn earlier and the Court may also order either that a caveat cease to be in force, or that its duration be extended: see SCR Pt 78 rr 69&#x2013;71.</text></p>
<p>
<text>The rules provide for three types of caveat:</text>
<l>
<li>
<lilabel>&#x2022;</lilabel>
<p><text>against an application for the grant or resealing: SCR Pt 78 r 66 &amp; [SCR Pt 78.66.6];</text></p></li>
<li>
<lilabel>&#x2022;</lilabel>
<p><text>relating to an informal testamentary document: SCR Pt 78 r 67 &amp; [SCR Pt 78.67.2];</text></p></li>
<li>
<lilabel>&#x2022;</lilabel>
<p><text>requiring proof in solemn form: SCR Pt 78 r 68 &amp; [SCR Pt 78.68.2].</text></p></li></l></p>
<p>
<text>The general caveat under SCR Pt 78 78.66 is the appropriate caveat where the caveator alleges invalidity other than want of due execution: <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseref ID="cr003022" spanref="cr003022-001"><ci:reporter value="urj"/><ci:refnum num="BC9201798"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Ragany v Pusztai</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr003022-001"> (NSWSC, Powell J, No 104605/92, 19 June 1992, unreported, BC9201798)</ci:span></citefragment></ci:content></ci:cite>. A caveat under SCR Pt 78 78.68 requiring proof in solemn is limited to matters relating to due execution of the will. Practitioners should be aware of the distinction between a general caveat and a caveat requiring proof only in a solemn form: <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseinfo><ci:decisiondate year="1992"/></ci:caseinfo><ci:caseref ID="cr003023" spanref="cr003023-001"><ci:reporter value="NSWLR"/><ci:volume num="27"/><ci:page num="232"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Azzopardi v Smart</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr003023-001">(1992) 27 NSWLR 232</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="37065" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite> and see [SCR Pt 78.68.5]</text></p>
</bodytext>
</level><level id="UCPN_SC.SGM_UCPN.SC.SCR70.PT78.R66-15" leveltype="para0" subdoc="true" toc-caption="[SCR Pt 78.66.15] Basis for caveat"><heading searchtype="COMMENTARY"><edpnum><refpt id="UCPN.SC.SCR70.PT78.R66-15" type="ext"/>[SCR Pt 78.66.15] </edpnum><title>Basis for caveat</title></heading>
<bodytext searchtype="COMMENTARY">
<p>
<text>A caveator must have a relevant interest in the estate: <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseref ID="cr003024" spanref="cr003024-001"><ci:reporter value="urj"/><ci:refnum num="BC9201798"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Ragany v Pusztai</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr003024-001"> (NSWSC, Powell J, No 104605/92, 19 June 1992, unreported, BC9201798)</ci:span></citefragment></ci:content></ci:cite>; <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseref ID="cr003025" spanref="cr003025-001"><ci:reporter value="urj"/><ci:refnum num="BC9201821"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Public Trustee v Mullane</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr003025-001"> (NSWSC, Powell J, 12 June 1992, BC9201821)</ci:span></citefragment></ci:content></ci:cite>. A relevant interest exists if the caveator has a potential entitlement to share in the estate, and that interest will be affected by the grant of probate or administration: <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseref ID="cr003026" spanref="cr003026-001" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="StRQd"/><ci:edition><ci:date year="1943"/></ci:edition><ci:page num="137"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Re Devoy; Fitzgerald &amp; Pender v Fitzgerald</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr003026-001" status="unval">[1943] St R Qd 137</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="7197" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>; <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseref ID="cr003027" spanref="cr003027-001"><ci:reporter value="urj"/><ci:refnum num="BC9201798"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Ragany v Pusztai</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr003027-001"> (NSWSC, Powell J, No 104605/92, 19 June 1992, unreported, BC9201798)</ci:span></citefragment></ci:content></ci:cite> (a right under a missing will, or an entitlement on intestacy). A mere judgment creditor of the deceased is not a person who has standing to lodge a caveat: <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Whiteley v Clune; Estate of Whiteley</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> (NSWSC, Powell J, 19 June 1993, unreported)</citefragment></ci:content></ci:cite> (former spouse &#x2014; judgment creditor in Family Court proceedings). A caveat is inappropriate where the plaintiff's claim is based upon an alleged agreement to make mutual wills: see [SCR Pt 78.49.10].</text></p>
<p>
<text>For a full discussion on standing to lodge a caveat see K Mason and L G Handler, <emph typestyle="it">Wills, Probate and Administration NSW</emph>, looseleaf, LexisNexis Butterworths, Sydney, at [1677.4] A person who lodges a caveat without reasonable grounds may be ordered to pay the applicant&#x2019;s costs: <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseinfo><ci:decisiondate year="1929"/></ci:caseinfo><ci:caseref ID="cr003028" spanref="cr003028-001" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="SRNSW"/><ci:volume num="29"/><ci:page num="559"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref ID="cr003029" spanref="cr003029-002" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="WNNSW"/><ci:volume num="47"/><ci:page num="176"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">In the Will of O'Driscoll</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr003028-001" status="unval">(1929) 29 SR (NSW) 559</ci:span>; <ci:span spanid="cr003029-002" status="unval">47 WN (NSW) 176</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="37064" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>. The repeated filing of unjustified caveats is an abuse of process and may be restrained by injunction: <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseref ID="cr003030" spanref="cr003030-001"><ci:reporter value="urj"/><ci:refnum num="BC9201798"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Ragany v Pusztai</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr003030-001"> (NSWSC, Powell J, No 104605/92, 19 June 1992, unreported, BC9201798)</ci:span></citefragment></ci:content></ci:cite>.</text></p>
</bodytext>
